      "message": "@ed@tanous.net @molberding@nvidia.com\n\nThanks for the clear feedbacks on this commit and I want to make sure I\u0027m responding to the actual concern rather than guessing. \n\nFirst of all, we will abandon the `yield_context` overload of `sendRecvMsg` regardless of what we decide below, I understand that this is not the right approach here.\n\nWhat we actually need is a way for D-Bus method handler to wait on a async operation before sending the reply(in our case, RESET-related operation) and I noticed that `sd-bus` has already documented such a mechanism: a method callback may return a positive integer and emit the reply later, from any continuation it chooses.\n\nCheck here for more details.(https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/sd_bus_add_object.html#)\n\nI would like to add a simple `sdbusplus` wrapper over that mechanism that consists of no coroutine but callback-based way to defer the reply, and then use it in the dbus-sensors handlers that motivated this patch. Before I post anything for review, I would like to check the direction with you:\n\n1. Is the objection on this patch specifically about `boost::coroutines`, or about any form of asynchronous reply from a D-Bus method handler? Marc\u0027s note that \"this was previously non-blocking without coroutines\" reads to me as the former, but I want to be certain before redesigning the `dbus-sensors` side.\n\n2. Given Ed\u0027s note that `sdbusplus` shouldn\u0027t have shipped coroutine support in the first place, would a non-coroutine async-reply API in sdbusplus be acceptable in principle? It is strictly additive and doesn\u0027t touch `register_method` or the coroutine path.\n\n3. I would only use the prototyped implementation `register_deferred_method(...)` for control-plane handlers(such as Reset), and let the sensor hotpaths stay on the existing callback API. Does that match how you would want it scoped?\n\n4. Before I push the `sdbusplus` change, is there an existing pattern in OpenBMC you woulf prefer here? If so, I would rather adopt it than introduce a new API.\n\nThanks for your time considering the above questions!",
